{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c11be16c-4280-403f-a907-cf90cef1a463","content":"Here are the five breaking changes you'll hit upgrading to .NET 10:\n\n**1. `[InlineArray]` + explicit `[StructLayout]`**\n.NET 10 **disallows** explicit layout on inline array types. Remove the `[StructLayout]` attribute — the runtime now controls layout. Your `Size = 64` will be inferred from `[InlineArray(16)]` × element size.\n\n**2. `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux**\nNow returns the **filesystem type** (e.g. `\"ext4\"`, `\"tmpfs\"`) instead of the mount path. Update any string comparisons to match filesystem type names.\n\n**3. NU1510 — pruned dependency warnings**\n.NET 10 enables **dependency pruning** during restore. Suppress with:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <SuppressDependencyPruning>true</SuppressDependencyPruning>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\nOr fix by removing unused package references the warnings identify.\n\n**4. Transitive NuGet audit**\n`NuGetAuditMode` now defaults to **`all`** (was `direct`), so transitive vulnerabilities surface. Run `dotnet list package --vulnerable --include-transitive` and upgrade affected packages. To revert to old behavior:\n```xml\n<NuGetAuditMode>direct</NuGetAuditMode>\n```\n\n**5. `FilePatternMatch.Stem` nullability**\n`Stem` changed from `string?` to **`string`** (non-nullable). Null checks won't break compilation but are now unnecessary and may trigger `CS8073` warnings. Remove the `null` comparisons.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d12867f0-d817-4351-8c26-0ffe17dfc4b6","outputTokens":406,"requestId":"A445:2CEFFD:3A333F:424B2E:6A03D17C"},"id":"f55df0ad-923c-4630-8df9-1070b912f648","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:19:02.060Z","parentId":"f00d1014-23d4-4820-be0a-fd3e53c21ea5"}
